edit-outline","\u002Fdocs\u002Fweb\u002Ftiptap","1.docs\u002Fweb\u002Ftiptap",[504],{"title":505,"path":506,"stem":507},"Snippets","\u002Fdocs\u002Fweb\u002Ftiptap\u002Fsnippets","1.docs\u002Fweb\u002Ftiptap\u002Fsnippets",{"id":509,"title":510,"authors":511,"badge":517,"body":518,"date":713,"description":714,"extension":715,"image":716,"meta":718,"navigation":722,"path":723,"seo":724,"stem":725,"__hash__":726},"posts\u002F3.blog\u002F2017\u002Fgolang-go-get-from-gitlab.md","Golang: go get from GitLab",[512],{"name":513,"to":514,"avatar":515},"Alexander Trost","https:\u002F\u002Fgithub.com\u002Fgalexrt",{"src":516},"\u002Fimages\u002Fprofile-picture.jpg",null,{"type":519,"value":520,"toc":705},"minimark",[521,530,547,559,564,582,585,593,604,607,613,628,636,641,647,688,692,698,701],[522,523,524,525,529],"p",{},"I just now came across the problem that I created a repository on a private GitLab instance for a Golang project and could not just use ",[526,527,528],"code",{},"go get ..."," to get it.\nAfter a short Google search, I came across this StackOverflow question and thankfully it had a working answer.",[522,531,532,533,540,541,546],{},"The original StackOverflow question can be found here: ",[534,535,539],"a",{"href":536,"rel":537},"https:\u002F\u002Fstackoverflow.com\u002Fquestions\u002F29707689\u002Fhow-do-you-use-golang-with-a-private-gitlab-repo\u002F37844256#37844256",[538],"nofollow","StackOverflow - how do you use golang with a private gitlab repo?",", the question was asked by User ",[534,542,545],{"href":543,"rel":544},"https:\u002F\u002Fstackoverflow.com\u002Fusers\u002F2904939\u002Fjames-fremen",[538],"James Fremen",".",[548,549,550,556],"blockquote",{},[522,551,552],{},[553,554,555],"strong",{},"NOTE",[522,557,558],{},"I will quote the question and answer which worked here so it is sort of archived here.",[560,561,563],"h2",{"id":562},"the-original-question","The original question",[548,565,566,569],{},[522,567,568],{},"GitLab is a free, open-source way to host private .git repositories but it does not seem to work with golang. When you create a project it generates a URL of the form:",[570,571,575],"pre",{"className":572,"code":573,"language":574,"meta":573,"style":573},"language-bash shiki shiki-themes material-theme-lighter material-theme material-theme-palenight","","bash",[526,576,577],{"__ignoreMap":573},[578,579],"span",{"class":580,"line":581},"line",1,[522,583,584],{},"git@1.2.3.4:private-developers\u002Fproject.git",[570,586,591],{"className":587,"code":589,"language":590},[588],"language-text","> where: 1.2.3.4 is the IP address of the gitlab server private-developers is a user group which has access to the private repo\n>\n> Golang 1.2.1 doesn't seem to understand this syntax.\n>\n>```bash\ngo get git@1.2.3.4:private-developers\u002Fproject.git\n","text",[526,592,589],{"__ignoreMap":573},[548,594,595,598],{},[522,596,597],{},"results in:",[570,599,600],{"className":572,"code":573,"language":574,"meta":573,"style":573},[526,601,602],{"__ignoreMap":573},[578,603],{"class":580,"line":581},[522,605,606],{},"package git@23.251.148.129\u002Fproject.git: unrecognized import path \"git@1.2.3.4\u002Fproject.git\"",[570,608,611],{"className":609,"code":610,"language":590},[588],"> Is there a way to get this to work?\n>\n> thanks!\n\nAuthor of the question [James Fremen](https:\u002F\u002Fstackoverflow.com\u002Fusers\u002F2904939\u002Fjames-fremen)\n\n## The answer that worked for me\n> Run this command:\n>\n>```bash\ngit config --global url.\"git@1.2.3.4:\".insteadOf \"https:\u002F\u002F1.2.3.4\u002F\"\n",[526,612,610],{"__ignoreMap":573},[548,614,615,625],{},[522,616,617,618,621,622,546],{},"Assuming you have the correct privileges to ",[526,619,620],{},"git clone"," the repository, this will make go get work for all repos on server ",[526,623,624],{},"1.2.3.4",[522,626,627],{},"I tested this to work with go version 1.6.2 and 1.8.",[522,629,630,631],{},"Author of the answer ",[534,632,635],{"href":633,"rel":634},"https:\u002F\u002Fstackoverflow.com\u002Fusers\u002F616644\u002Frick-smith",[538],"Rick Smith",[637,638,640],"h3",{"id":639},"example-for-dns-names","Example for DNS names",[522,642,643,644,546],{},"So for example with dns names, it would be for a gitlab running at ",[526,645,646],{},"gitlab.example.com",[570,648,650],{"className":572,"code":649,"language":574,"meta":573,"style":573},"git config --global url.\"git@gitlab.example.com:\".insteadOf \"https:\u002F\u002Fexample.com\u002F\"\n",[526,651,652],{"__ignoreMap":573},[578,653,654,657,661,664,667,671,674,676,679,682,685],{"class":580,"line":581},[578,655,221],{"class":656},"sBMFI",[578,658,660],{"class":659},"sfazB"," config",[578,662,663],{"class":659}," --global",[578,665,666],{"class":659}," url.",[578,668,670],{"class":669},"sMK4o","\"",[578,672,673],{"class":659},"git@gitlab.example.com:",[578,675,670],{"class":669},[578,677,678],{"class":659},".insteadOf",[578,680,681],{"class":669}," \"",[578,683,684],{"class":659},"https:\u002F\u002Fexample.com\u002F",[578,686,687],{"class":669},"\"\n",[560,689,691],{"id":690},"summary","Summary",[522,693,694,695,546],{},"With that change, you can now successfully run ",[526,696,697],{},"go get gitlab.example.com\u002Fexample-user\u002Fexample-project",[522,699,700],{},"Have Fun!",[702,703,704],"style",{},"html .light .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-light);background: var(--shiki-light-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-light-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-light-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-light-text-decoration);}html.light .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-light);background: var(--shiki-light-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-light-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-light-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-light-text-decoration);}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .dark .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-dark);background: var(--shiki-dark-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-dark-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-dark-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-dark-text-decoration);}html.dark .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-dark);background: var(--shiki-dark-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-dark-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-dark-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-dark-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sBMFI, html code.shiki .sBMFI{--shiki-light:#E2931D;--shiki-default:#FFCB6B;--shiki-dark:#FFCB6B}html pre.shiki code .sfazB, html code.shiki .sfazB{--shiki-light:#91B859;--shiki-default:#C3E88D;--shiki-dark:#C3E88D}html pre.shiki code .sMK4o, html code.shiki .sMK4o{--shiki-light:#39ADB5;--shiki-default:#89DDFF;--shiki-dark:#89DDFF}",{"title":573,"searchDepth":706,"depth":706,"links":707},2,[708,712],{"id":562,"depth":706,"text":563,"children":709},[710],{"id":639,"depth":711,"text":640},3,{"id":690,"depth":706,"text":691},"2017-06-02T14:39:01+02:00","I just now came across the problem that I created a repository on a private GitLab instance for a Golang project and could not just use go get ... to get it.\nAfter a short Google search, I came across this StackOverflow question and thankfully it had a working answer.","md",{"src":717},"\u002Fblog\u002Fcovers\u002Fgo-logo_lightblue.png",{"tags":719},[720,721],"Golang","GitLab",true,"\u002Fblog\u002F2017\u002Fgolang-go-get-from-gitlab",{"title":510,"description":714},"3.blog\u002F2017\u002Fgolang-go-get-from-gitlab","8rTZgp0SozHD0tnkmq_mUkTmeShkGwPpReJh0hy8Gv4",[728,733],{"title":729,"path":730,"stem":731,"description":732,"children":-1},"GitLab + Kubernetes: Running CI Runners in Kubernetes","\u002Fblog\u002F2017\u002Fgitlab-kubernetes-running-ci-runners-in-kubernetes","3.blog\u002F2017\u002Fgitlab-kubernetes-running-ci-runners-in-kubernetes","How to run GitLab CI Runners in Kubernetes using the GitLab CI Runner's Kubernetes executor.",{"title":734,"path":735,"stem":736,"description":737,"children":-1},"Google Cloud: Enterprise Grade Hybrid Cloud with Kubernetes Cluster Federation","\u002Fblog\u002F2017\u002Fgoogle-cloud-enterprise-grade-hybrid-cloud-with-kubernetes-cluster-federation","3.blog\u002F2017\u002Fgoogle-cloud-enterprise-grade-hybrid-cloud-with-kubernetes-cluster-federation","These are my thoughts and notes about the presentation and overall the Google Cloud Kubernetes Federation event itself.",1776891358215]